				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/boogey-man23" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2362395); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2362395&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610163883" alt="Boogey_Man23" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2362395)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/boogey-man23" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2362395); return false;" >Boogey_Man23</a></span> <span class="odate time_1506098622 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">22 Sep 2017 16:43</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3599558">
									

<p>Oh sorry, do you mean the report of the containment breach at the start? I do have an explanation in mind as to what happens and how, but much of it boils down to security guard alarm response SOPs, and those being fumbled in a specifically plot-convenient way. I didn't think it would be a good way to start the tale so it's only referred to from Bert's viewpoint, but all he knows is that they got told where to go and not for what.</p>
<p>Though if it might help for context.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Summary&nbsp;of&nbsp;Preceding&nbsp;Events</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Summary&nbsp;of&nbsp;Preceding&nbsp;Events</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>SCP-1087 was going to be used in experiments that night. Upon entering the habitat the creature was unable to be located. Responding containment technician found damage to containment habitat indicating likely escape. Site security monitoring station was contacted, trainee-guard took details of call.</p>
<p>Now, their protocol at this time should be: Send first message with <span style="text-decoration: underline;">all</span> information to the MTF, send second message for Site-wide general alert with censored files; so everyone is aware of MTF operating in area but not any classified info. (Yes, these SOPs are designed to fail in exactly the way that my story plays out.) What they do is: Draft up the Site-wide general alert, then include the responding MTF on the recipients list 'to save time by sending just one message'.</p>
<p>Their trainer, keeping less than a hawk-like eye on them, asks &quot;So you notified the MTF and sent the Site-wide breach alert, right?&quot;. &quot;Yep,&quot; the trainee responds. And the trainer doesn't find out what that actually means until he's getting yelled at by the MTF Captain.</p>
<p>At that point the MTF gets the proper files, acquires the proper equipment, and goes to meet up with the first responders.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Huh, I wonder if <em>that</em> should have been worked into the story somehow&#8230;?</p>

							</div>

								
					
